properties.Name: Chaplain's House
properties.History: Largely funded by Mrs. Julia Douglas Merritt.

properties.Name: DeLancy House
properties.History: Has been used as a faculty house, guest house, and meeting house.

properties.Name: Geneva Hall
properties.History: Originally housed all the offices, chapel, library, and student rooms until Trinity and the Middle Building were built.

properties.Name: Harris House
properties.History: Built by Miss Catherine Post who kept it as a college boarding house. Purchased by the College in 1837.

properties.Name: Kappa Sigma
properties.History: Built by Mr. Schermerhorn.

properties.Name: McDaniels House
properties.History: Named after Joseph Hertherington McDaniels (1840-1933), Professor of Greek 1868-1911 and 1997 Distinguished Faculty Awardee.

properties.Name: Merritt Hall
properties.History: Built from limestone and materials from the ruins of the old Medical College. Major byuilding funds donated by Mrs. Julia Douglas Merritt.

properties.Name: President's House
properties.History: Became property of the Colleges in 1883.

properties.Name: Rosenberg, Eaton, Albright, Lansing
properties.History: Rosenberg Hall (1994), Eaton Hall (1961), Albright Auditorium (1957), Lansing Hall (1954).

properties.Name: Sigma Phi
properties.History: Built by Mrs. Gavin Lawson, became the rectory for Trinity Church 1825-1852, and then sold to James Simons.

properties.Name: Barn
properties.History: Designed by John Harvey Associates Architects. Remodeled into a social center in 1979.

properties.Name: Bartlett Hall
properties.History: Named for President Murray Bartlett, 1919-1936. Renovated in 1993 by Hoffman, O'Brien, Look and Taube.

properties.Name: Blackwell House
properties.History: Purchased with funds from the William Smith grant in 1908 for $27,500.

properties.Name: Brent House
properties.History: Named for Bishop Charles Henry Brent.

properties.Name: Coxe Hall
properties.History: Named for the second Bishop of Episcopal Church Western NY, several relatives of whom had attended the Colleges.

properties.Name: Durfee Hall
properties.History: Named for both William Pitt Durfee and his son, Walter Hetherington Durfee, H. 1908. Both were professors of mathematics, deans, interim presidents.

properties.Name: Gulick Hall
properties.History: used as a dining hall/student union building.

properties.Name: Hale Hall
properties.History: Named for President Benjamin Hale, 1836-1858.

properties.Name: Medbery Hall
properties.History: Named in memory of two uncles of Miss Catherine Tuttle who gave the money to be used for a dormitory.

properties.Name: One Cloverleaf
properties.History: Purchased in the 1980's.

properties.Name: Smith Hall
properties.History: First academic building for the new William Smith College and was used largely as a science building for both colleges. The donor was William Smith.

properties.Name: Williams Hall
properties.History: Built as a gymnasium with a swimming pool in the basement and a track on the second floor. Converted to classrooms after Bristol was built.

properties.Name: Winn-Seeley Gymnasium
properties.History: Named for Marcia Winn and Janet Seeley, two William Smith faculty members who taught in the physical education department for many years.

properties.Name: Bristol Gymnasium
properties.History: Named for Robert Bristol, Hobart 1931, and long time member of trustees and principal donor.

properties.Name: Comstock House
properties.History: Named for Anna Botsford Comstock, friend of William Smith and the first woman to be named a member of the Board of Trustees.

properties.Name: Hirshson Hall
properties.History: Named after the Reverend Louis Melbourne Hirshson, who served as president of Hobart and William Smith Colleges from 1956 to 1966.

properties.Name: Miller House
properties.History: Named for Elizabeth Smith Miller, one of the area's active suffragists.

properties.Name: Stern Hall
properties.History: Donation from Herbert J. Stern. Houses the Political Science, Anthropology/Sociology, Economics, and Asian Languages and Cultures Departments.

properties.Name: Intercultural Affairs Center
properties.History: Purchased in 1981 to be used as Third World Cultural Center.

properties.Name: Emerson Hall
properties.History: Named for William Emerson, Chairman of Committee on Aims of the Colleges, and founder of the Emerson Society.

properties.Name: Finger Lakes Institute
properties.History: The house is a completely green facility using wind, solar, and geothermal energy.

properties.Name: McCormick House
properties.History: Named for Mary Ellen McCormick, Dean of William Smith College (1936-1944) in 1941.

properties.Name: Odell's Unit A
properties.History: Named for Professor Theodore T. Odell, Hobart 1920, and Professor of Biology from 1921-1965 and Distinguished faculty Awardee.

properties.Name: Odell's Unit B
properties.History: Named for Professor Theodore T. Odell, Hobart 1920, and Professor of Biology from 1921-1965 and Distinguished faculty Awardee.

properties.Name: Odell's Unit C
properties.History: Named for Professor Theodore T. Odell, Hobart 1920, and Professor of Biology from 1921-1965 and Distinguished faculty Awardee.

properties.Name: Stucco House
properties.History: Music Performance House (2005-6).

properties.Name: Trinity Hall
properties.History: President Hale was the architect and the Major contributor was Trinity Corporation of the Episcopalian Church at a sum of $7,000.

properties.Name: St. John's Chapel, Demarest Hall
properties.History: Chapel designed by Richard Upjohn. Mrs. Agnes Demarest was the primary donor for Demarest Hall.

properties.Name: Chi Phi
properties.History: Renovated after a fire during the 2005 Spring semester damaged the third floor.

properties.Name: Delta Chi
properties.History: Built by Reverend Henry Dwight

properties.Name: Warren Hunting Smith Library
properties.History: Named for Warren Hunting Smith, Trustee, the major donor to the building and grandnephew of William Smith.

properties.Name: Odell's Unit D
properties.History: Named for Professor Theodore T. Odell, Hobart 1920, and Professor of Biology from 1921-1965 and Distinguished faculty Awardee.

properties.Name: Scandling Center
properties.History: Named after William Scandling, '49, who created a new food service, SAGA, named after the Indian name for Geneva, Kanadesaga.

properties.Name: Zappler House
properties.History: Last owner Dr. Zappler.

properties.Name: Alumni House
properties.History: 1971-1974 Capuchin Father's Monastery, from whom the Colleges brought it in 1974.

properties.Name: Caird Hall
properties.History: Dedicated to James F. Caird '56 and his wife, Cynthia L. Caird, during Reunion 2007.

properties.Name: de Cordova Hall
properties.History: Dedicated at his 50th Renuion, deCordova Hall is named for Arthur E. deCordova '56.

properties.Name: Kappa Alpha
properties.History: Bought by the Kappa Alpha Society in 1952.

properties.Name: Bradford House
properties.History: Adobe house in Gothic Revival style. Renovated in April 2006 to house all admissions.

properties.Name: Centennial Center for Leadership
properties.History: Founded in commemoration of the William Smith Centennial Celebration in November 2008. Renovated and endowed as part of Campaign for the Colleges.

properties.Name: Durfee House
properties.History: Formerly Hobart Admissions, became the Communications building in July 2006.

properties.Name: Sill House
properties.History: Purchased by the colleges in 1939 and founded as the first co-op.
